default4.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultG
defaultovernment approach to reduce heat energy demand has been twofold
default – i)
default key policies to reduce the heat demand through insulation (such as ECO and CERT)
default,
default and 
defaultii) 
defaultlegislation on boilers to improve the efficiency of heat production. Both 
defaultof 
defaultthese policies
default, 
defaultcoupled with rising energy costs
default,
default have seen heat demand fall. 
defaultI
defaultmproving 
defaultbuilding standards in new builds has also had an impact. However, further progress could be made with insulation penetration
default,
default and it is unclear whether the Green Deal will provide sufficient impetus for the reductions to continue. In our 2013 FES scenarios
default both in Gone Green and Slow Progression uptake of insulation is lower than assumed in the 
defaultG
defaultovernment
default’s
default Green Deal Impact Assessment, whilst similar progress to historic trends is made in boiler energy savings.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;default5.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSince 2005, significant and continuing
default 
defaultincreases in energy prices, combined
default 
defaultwith 
defaultG
defaultovernment policies, have brought
default 
defaultabout substantial increases in residential
default 
defaultenergy efficiency.
default 
defaultInvestment in insulation and energy efficienc
defaulty programmes, heating controls and behaviour change can significantly reduce the demand for heat in an economic and sustainable way
default,
default and should be the highest priority on our pathway to meeting 2050 carbon reduction targets.
default&#xa0;
default5.2.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn the last 5-10 years, 
defaultsignificant savings have occurred through improved insulation, with cavity wall and loft insulation seeing the greatest energy demand
default 
defaultimprovements. This has been
default 
defaultprimarily due to 
defaultG
defaultovernment energy efficiency
default 
defaultschemes such as the Carbon Emission Reduction 
defaultTarget (CERT)
default,
default and the Community Energy Saving
default 
defaultProgramme (CESP) also contributing to
default 
defaultan increase in solid wall insulation. 
default&#xa0;
default5.3.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultWe have seen CERT and the previous EEC reduce domestic heat demand by around 10% in the last decade (roughly 30TWh 
defaultheat
default demand savi
defaultng annually). Since 2006 the savings derived from the legal requirement to install condensing boilers has reduced domestic gas demand further by around 10% (roughly 30TWh 
defaultgas
default demand saving annually). Our scenarios assess that a further 30-40TWh 
defaultof 
defaultannual g
defaultas demand savings will occur due to continued boiler replacement, under the existing legislation
default&#xa0;
