default&#xa0;default&#xa0;default6.1.
default&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultelectrification of heat using either air sourced or ground sourced heat pumps is expected to play a very significant role in the future management of domestic heat by 2050. However, there is still a role for gas in heat in 2050
default,
default as it is more economic to p
defaultrovide baseload heat for buildings with electric heat
default 
defaultpumps and use gas boilers as seasonal top up, than to remove gas altogether. This is because air source heat
default 
defaultpumps performance fall as outside temperature reduces, at the time when demand is highest. Th
defaultis has a significant impact on the need to supply proportionately more power and capacity on the electricity system to meet winter peaks. By balancing this with top up gas use
default,
default 2050 carbon targets can be met more economically than by using electricity alon
defaulte
default,
default by avoiding the significant investment in generating and network capacity that would be needed otherwise. The annual heat demand curve for 2050 from our 2013 FES is illustrated below:
